<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    Tessera privacy manifest.

    Scope rule (the hard lesson): declare a Required-Reason API category
    ONLY when a specific call in app or embedded-library code maps to that
    category's stated intent. `plutil -lint` only checks plist syntax — it
    does NOT validate that key names or reason codes are real. Cross-check
    against:
        Sentry — https://docs.sentry.io/platforms/apple/data-management/apple-privacy-manifest/
        Apple DevForums thread 770148 (ITMS-91056 reference cases)
    before adding anything to NSPrivacyAccessedAPITypes.

    What Tessera does that COULD trigger Required-Reason APIs:
      - FileManager.url(for: .applicationSupportDirectory, ...) for SoloStore
        → does NOT access file timestamps (it creates / locates a directory).
      - Data(contentsOf:) / data.write(to:options:[.atomic]) for SoloStore
        → reads/writes bytes; does not surface timestamp metadata to us.
      - GRDB / SQLite read of bundled tessera.sqlite
        → no Required-Reason API category in Apple's published list maps to
          SQLite query timing or pragma reads.
    Net result: nothing in NSPrivacyAccessedAPITypes. If Apple's submission
    validator flags a category we genuinely use, add it with the specific
    triggering call cited in a comment — not on speculation.
-->
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>NSPrivacyTracking</key>
    <false/>
    <key>NSPrivacyTrackingDomains</key>
    <array/>
    <key>NSPrivacyCollectedDataTypes</key>
    <array/>
    <key>NSPrivacyAccessedAPITypes</key>
    <array/>
</dict>
</plist>
